1
00:00:20,354 --> 00:00:23,273
Come now, Father, you should know better.

2
00:00:23,565 --> 00:00:27,027
You're not welcome here,
and especially not today.

3
00:00:27,110 --> 00:00:29,530
I've got no time to start old arguments.

4
00:00:29,613 --> 00:00:32,950
-We want only one thing.
-And what would that be?

5
00:00:33,575 --> 00:00:36,787
-This house.
-You want the house?

6
00:00:37,246 --> 00:00:38,664
We will take the house.

7
00:00:38,789 --> 00:00:40,624
Would you like my wife while you're at it?

8
00:00:40,749 --> 00:00:43,252
If you won't stand aside,
then we'll take it by force.

9
00:00:43,335 --> 00:00:46,797
And by what power? The hand of God?

10
00:00:47,047 --> 00:00:50,342
No, the fist of man.

11
00:00:51,635 --> 00:00:55,639
(MAN GRUNTING)

12
00:01:39,558 --> 00:01:42,519
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

13
00:01:57,534 --> 00:01:59,161
In the name of Heaven.

14
00:02:00,829 --> 00:02:02,247
My Lady?

15
00:02:09,254 --> 00:02:12,883
What's in there? What is it?
What's under the canvas?

16
00:02:13,592 --> 00:02:16,428
Father, answer me. What's in there?

17
00:02:16,928 --> 00:02:18,722
May God forgive me.

18
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:28,565
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

19
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:11,858
-What do you think of this? Will it do?
-The late 1970s?

20
00:03:11,942 --> 00:03:14,528
You'd be better off in a bin bag.
Hold on, listen to this.

21
00:03:14,611 --> 00:03:16,113
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

22
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:20,367
Ian Dury and The Blockheads.
Number one in 1979.

23
00:03:20,450 --> 00:03:22,369
You're a punk!

24
00:03:22,452 --> 00:03:23,662
# It's good to be a lunatic #

25
00:03:23,787 --> 00:03:28,333
That's what you are, a big old punk
with a bit of rockabilly thrown in.

26
00:03:28,458 --> 00:03:30,877
-Do you want to go and see him?
-How do you mean, in concert?

27
00:03:31,002 --> 00:03:32,295
What else is the Tardis for?

28
00:03:32,379 --> 00:03:34,464
I can take you to the Battle of Trafalgar,

29
00:03:34,589 --> 00:03:38,218
the First Antigravity Olympics,
Caesar crossing the Rubicon

30
00:03:38,301 --> 00:03:42,472
or Ian Dury at the Top Rank, Sheffield,
England, Earth, 21st November 1979,

31
00:03:42,556 --> 00:03:44,015
what do you think?

32
00:03:44,599 --> 00:03:46,810
-Sheffield it is!
-Hold on tight.

33
00:03:52,899 --> 00:03:56,153
(HIT ME WITH YOUR RHYTHM STICK BY
IAN DURY AND THE BLOCKHEADS PLAYING)

34
00:03:56,278 --> 00:03:59,948
Landing!

35
00:04:05,078 --> 00:04:07,664
1979! Hell of a year!

36
00:04:07,789 --> 00:04:11,710
China invades Vietnam.
The Muppet Movie, love that film.

37
00:04:11,835 --> 00:04:16,339
Margaret Thatcher. Skylab falls to Earth
with a little help from me.

38
00:04:16,423 --> 00:04:18,925
Nearly took off my thumb,
and I like my thumb.

39
00:04:19,009 --> 00:04:23,513
I need my thumb.
I'm very attached to...my thumb.

40
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:29,478
1879. Same difference.

41
00:04:29,561 --> 00:04:33,356
You will explain your presence,
and the nakedness of this girl.

42
00:04:34,024 --> 00:04:36,985
-Are we in Scotland?
-How can you be ignorant of that?

43
00:04:37,068 --> 00:04:39,571
(SCOTTISH ACCENT)
I'm dazed and confused.

44
00:04:39,696 --> 00:04:43,909
I've been chasing this wee naked child
over hill and over dale.

45
00:04:43,992 --> 00:04:46,870
Isn't that right, you timorous beastie?

46
00:04:47,370 --> 00:04:52,042
(SCOTTISH ACCENT) Och, aye.
I've been "oot" and "a boot."

47
00:04:52,125 --> 00:04:54,377
-No, don't do that.
-Hoots, mon?

48
00:04:54,461 --> 00:04:56,421
No, really don't. Really.

49
00:04:56,546 --> 00:04:58,673
Will you identify yourself, sir?

50
00:04:58,757 --> 00:05:03,678
I'm Doctor James McCrimmon
from the township of Balamory.

51
00:05:04,346 --> 00:05:06,556
I have my credentials, if I may?

52
00:05:12,729 --> 00:05:16,233
As you can see, a doctorate
from the University of Edinburgh.

53
00:05:16,608 --> 00:05:18,860
I trained under Doctor Bell himself.

54
00:05:18,944 --> 00:05:20,779
WOMAN: Let them approach.

55
00:05:20,862 --> 00:05:24,658
-I don't think that's wise, ma'am.
-Let them approach.

56
00:05:27,244 --> 00:05:31,456
You will approach the carriage,
and show all due deference.

57
00:05:44,469 --> 00:05:49,182
Rose, might I introduce
Her Majesty Queen Victoria,

58
00:05:49,307 --> 00:05:51,935
Empress of India and Defender of the Faith.

59
00:05:52,060 --> 00:05:53,854
Rose Tyler, ma'am.

60
00:05:53,937 --> 00:05:57,399
And my apologies for being so naked.

61
00:05:57,482 --> 00:06:00,360
I've had five daughters. It's nothing to me.

62
00:06:00,443 --> 00:06:04,281
But you, Doctor, show me these credentials.

63
00:06:08,410 --> 00:06:10,328
Why didn't you say so immediately?

64
00:06:10,412 --> 00:06:12,205
It states clearly here

65
00:06:12,289 --> 00:06:15,417
that you have been appointed
by the Lord Provost as my protector.

66
00:06:15,542 --> 00:06:18,461
Does it? Yes, it does. Good. Good.

67
00:06:18,545 --> 00:06:22,883
Erm, then let me ask,
why is Your Majesty travelling by road

68
00:06:22,966 --> 00:06:25,302
when there's a train
all the way to Aberdeen?

69
00:06:25,427 --> 00:06:29,180
-A tree on the line.
-An accident?

70
00:06:29,639 --> 00:06:33,184
I am the Queen of the United Kingdom
of Great Britain and Ireland.

71
00:06:33,268 --> 00:06:37,647
-Everything around me tends to be planned.
-An assassination attempt?

72
00:06:37,814 --> 00:06:40,483
What, seriously?
There's people out to kill you?

73
00:06:40,567 --> 00:06:43,361
I'm quite used to staring down
the barrel of a gun.

74
00:06:43,486 --> 00:06:46,823
Sir Robert MaclLeish
lives but 10 miles hence.

75
00:06:46,907 --> 00:06:48,366
We've sent word ahead.

76
00:06:48,491 --> 00:06:51,328
He'll shelter us for tonight,
then we can reach Balmoral tomorrow.

77
00:06:51,453 --> 00:06:55,874
This Doctor and his timorous beastie
will come with us.

78
00:06:55,999 --> 00:06:57,334
Yes, ma'am.

79
00:06:57,417 --> 00:06:59,586
We'd better get moving.
It's almost nightfall.

80
00:06:59,669 --> 00:07:04,215
Indeed, and there are stories of wolves
in these parts.

81
00:07:04,299 --> 00:07:07,552
Fanciful tales,
intended to scare the children,

82
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:10,680
but good for the blood, I think. Drive on.

83
00:07:13,850 --> 00:07:15,852
ROSE: It's funny, though,
'cause you say assassination,

84
00:07:15,936 --> 00:07:18,980
and you just think of Kennedy and stuff,
not her.

85
00:07:19,105 --> 00:07:23,902
18797
She's had, oh, six attempts on her life.

86
00:07:24,027 --> 00:07:25,946
And I'll tell you something else.

87
00:07:26,029 --> 00:07:27,781
-We just met Queen Victoria.
-I know!

88
00:07:27,864 --> 00:07:29,574
-What a laugh!
-She was just sitting there!

89
00:07:29,699 --> 00:07:33,995
-Like a stamp.
-I want her to say, "We are not amused.”

90
00:07:34,079 --> 00:07:36,081
I bet you 5 quid I can make her say it.

91
00:07:36,206 --> 00:07:38,208
Well, if I gambled on that,

92
00:07:38,291 --> 00:07:40,502
it would be an abuse of my privilege
as a traveller in time.

93
00:07:40,585 --> 00:07:42,170
-10 quid.
-Done.

94
00:07:53,765 --> 00:07:56,393
I can't do this. It's treason.

95
00:07:57,727 --> 00:08:00,397
Then your wife
will suffer the consequences.

96
00:08:01,064 --> 00:08:04,609
Believe me, Sir Robert,
she will be devoured.

97
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:25,005
-Your Majesty.
-Sir Robert.

98
00:08:25,213 --> 00:08:28,925
My apologies for the emergency.
And how is Lady Isobel?

99
00:08:29,009 --> 00:08:32,220
She's indisposed, I'm afraid.

100
00:08:32,303 --> 00:08:34,723
She's gone to Edinburgh for the season,

101
00:08:35,140 --> 00:08:38,101
and she's taken the cook with her,
the kitchens are barely stocked.

102
00:08:38,184 --> 00:08:40,687
I wouldn't blame Your Majesty
if you wanted to ride on.

103
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:43,857
Not at all.
I've had quite enough carriage exercise,

104
00:08:43,940 --> 00:08:48,528
and this is charming, if rustic.

105
00:08:48,611 --> 00:08:51,448
It's my first visit to this house.

106
00:08:51,698 --> 00:08:55,785
My late husband spoke of it often,
the Torchwood Estate.

107
00:08:57,162 --> 00:09:02,250
Now, shall we go inside?
And please excuse the naked girl.

108
00:09:02,333 --> 00:09:05,211
-Sorry!
-She's a feral child.

109
00:09:05,295 --> 00:09:07,756
I bought her for sixpence
in old London town.

110
00:09:07,839 --> 00:09:09,424
It was her or the Elephant Man, so...

111
00:09:09,507 --> 00:09:14,095
Thinks he's funny, but I'm so not amused.
What do you think, ma'am?

112
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:17,682
It hardly matters. Shall we proceed?

113
00:09:19,392 --> 00:09:20,977
So close.

114
00:09:22,812 --> 00:09:25,273
Mackeson and Ramsay,
you will escort the property. Hurry up.

115
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:26,816
-Yes, sir.
-Yes, sir.

116
00:09:33,156 --> 00:09:34,491
So what's in there, then?

117
00:09:34,574 --> 00:09:38,995
Property of the Crown.
You will dismiss any further thoughts, sir.

118
00:09:39,871 --> 00:09:44,334
The rest of you, go to the rear of the house.
Assume the designated positions.

119
00:09:44,459 --> 00:09:47,504
-You heard the orders, positions.
-Sir.

120
00:09:47,629 --> 00:09:49,923
SOLDIER: You two, come with me...

121
00:10:01,935 --> 00:10:04,729
(SHUSHING)

122
00:10:14,114 --> 00:10:15,573
Guard it with your life.

123
00:10:21,454 --> 00:10:25,333
This, I take it, is the famous endeavour.

124
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:30,046
All my father's work.
Built by hand in his final years.

125
00:10:30,547 --> 00:10:33,299
It became something of an obsession.
He spent his money on this,

126
00:10:33,383 --> 00:10:35,885
rather than caring for the house or himself.

127
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:38,138
I wish I'd met him. I like him.

128
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:40,974
-That thing's beautiful, can I...
-Help yourself.

129
00:10:41,099 --> 00:10:44,227
-What did he model it on?
-I know nothing about it.

130
00:10:44,310 --> 00:10:45,895
To be honest,

131
00:10:45,979 --> 00:10:48,731
most of us thought him a little,
shall we say, eccentric.

132
00:10:51,693 --> 00:10:55,905
I wish now I'd spent more time with him
and listened to his stories.

133
00:10:57,949 --> 00:10:59,826
It's a bit rubbish.

134
00:10:59,909 --> 00:11:02,453
How many prisms has it got?
Way too many!

135
00:11:02,579 --> 00:11:05,623
The magnification's gone right over the top.
That's a stupid kind of...

136
00:11:05,707 --> 00:11:06,916
-Am I being rude again?
-Yep!

137
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,211
But it's pretty! It's very pretty.

138
00:11:10,295 --> 00:11:12,755
And the imagination of it
should be applauded.

139
00:11:12,881 --> 00:11:16,092
Hmm. I thought you might disapprove,
Your Majesty.

140
00:11:16,176 --> 00:11:19,929
Stargazing. Isn't that a bit fanciful?

141
00:11:20,597 --> 00:11:24,934
You could easily not be amused,
or something. No?

142
00:11:26,019 --> 00:11:29,939
This device surveys
the infinite work of God.

143
00:11:30,023 --> 00:11:31,733
What could be finer?

144
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:34,986
Sir Robert's father was an example
to us all,

145
00:11:35,069 --> 00:11:38,865
a polymath,
steeped in astronomy and the sciences,

146
00:11:38,990 --> 00:11:42,452
yet equally well-versed
in folklore and fairy tales.

147
00:11:42,577 --> 00:11:45,246
Stars and magic. I like him more and more.

148
00:11:46,623 --> 00:11:49,459
Oh, my late husband enjoyed his company.

149
00:11:50,418 --> 00:11:54,881
Prince Albert himself was acquainted
with many rural superstitions,

150
00:11:54,964 --> 00:11:56,799
coming as he did from Saxe-Coburg.

151
00:11:56,883 --> 00:11:58,384
That's Bavaria.

152
00:11:59,969 --> 00:12:04,974
When Albert was told about your local wolf,
he was transported.

153
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:07,060
So what's this wolf, then?

154
00:12:07,727 --> 00:12:10,438
-It's just a story.
-Then tell it.

155
00:12:14,317 --> 00:12:17,070
-It's said that...
-Excuse me, sir.

156
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:20,823
Perhaps Her Majesty's party
could repair to their rooms.

157
00:12:21,199 --> 00:12:22,825
It's almost dark.

158
00:12:24,953 --> 00:12:27,580
Of course. Yes, of course.

159
00:12:27,664 --> 00:12:28,998
And then supper.

160
00:12:29,123 --> 00:12:32,877
And could we find some clothes
for Miss Tyler?

161
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:38,174
-I'm tired of nakedness.
-It's not amusing, is it?

162
00:12:40,343 --> 00:12:43,513
Sir Robert, your wife
must have left some clothes. See to it.

163
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:47,141
We shall dine at 7:00,
and talk some more of this wolf.

164
00:12:47,684 --> 00:12:51,187
After all, there is a full moon tonight.

165
00:12:52,522 --> 00:12:54,148
So there is, ma'am.

166
00:13:28,599 --> 00:13:30,059
(LAUGHING)

167
00:13:48,578 --> 00:13:49,579
(SCREAMS)

168
00:14:09,223 --> 00:14:11,851
They came through the house in silence.

169
00:14:11,934 --> 00:14:15,521
They took the steward and the master,
and my lady.

170
00:14:15,605 --> 00:14:17,815
Listen, I've got a friend.

171
00:14:17,899 --> 00:14:20,026
He's called the Doctor.
He'll know what to do.

172
00:14:20,109 --> 00:14:23,279
-You've got to come with me.
-Oh, but I can't, Miss.

173
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:26,282
-What's your name?
-Flora.

174
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:29,369
Flora, we'll be safe.

175
00:14:29,452 --> 00:14:31,954
There's more people arrived downstairs,
soldiers and everything.

176
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:35,291
They can help us. I promise.

177
00:14:35,416 --> 00:14:38,961
Come on. Okay? Come on.

178
00:14:50,807 --> 00:14:53,309
Oh, Miss, I did warn you.

179
00:14:55,520 --> 00:14:59,357
He's not dead, I don't think.
He must be drugged or something.

180
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:00,650
(MUFFLED SCREAMING)

181
00:15:11,452 --> 00:15:15,456
Your companion begs an apology, Doctor.
Her clothing has somewhat delayed her.

182
00:15:15,540 --> 00:15:17,667
Oh, that's all right.
Save her a wee bit of ham.

183
00:15:17,750 --> 00:15:20,169
The feral child could probably eat it raw.

184
00:15:20,294 --> 00:15:21,754
(LAUGHING)

185
00:15:21,838 --> 00:15:25,550
-Very wise, ma'am. Very witty.
-Slightly witty, perhaps.

186
00:15:26,008 --> 00:15:30,680
I know you rarely get the chance to dine
with me, Captain, but don't get too excited.

187
00:15:31,514 --> 00:15:35,852
I shall contain my wit
in case I do you further injury.

188
00:15:36,185 --> 00:15:37,812
Yes, ma'am. Sorry, ma'am.

189
00:15:37,895 --> 00:15:40,898
Besides, we're all waiting on Sir Robert.
Come, sir.

190
00:15:40,982 --> 00:15:43,734
-You promised us a tale of nightmares.
-VICTORIA: Indeed.

191
00:15:44,026 --> 00:15:45,695
Since my husband's death,

192
00:15:45,820 --> 00:15:48,906
I find myself with more of a taste
for supernatural fiction.

193
00:15:49,073 --> 00:15:50,992
You must miss him.

194
00:15:52,034 --> 00:15:53,369
Very much.

195
00:15:56,956 --> 00:15:58,458
Oh, completely.

196
00:16:00,585 --> 00:16:02,545
And that's the charm of a ghost story,
isn't it?

197
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:05,173
Not the scares and chills,
that's just for children,

198
00:16:05,256 --> 00:16:10,386
but the hope of some contact
with the great beyond.

199
00:16:11,471 --> 00:16:16,058
We all want some message from that place.

200
00:16:16,893 --> 00:16:21,147
It's the Creator's greatest mystery
that we're allowed no such consolation.

201
00:16:23,608 --> 00:16:25,568
The dead stay silent,

202
00:16:28,529 --> 00:16:30,156
and we must wait.

203
00:16:34,494 --> 00:16:39,665
Come, begin your tale, Sir Robert.
There's a chill in the air.

204
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:44,170
The wind is howling through the eaves.
Tell us of monsters.

205
00:16:47,590 --> 00:16:49,425
Don't make a sound.

206
00:16:50,176 --> 00:16:53,804
They said if we scream or shout,
then he will slaughter us.

207
00:16:53,888 --> 00:16:58,851
But he's in a cage. He's a prisoner.
He's the same as us.

208
00:16:58,935 --> 00:17:03,981
He's nothing like us.
That creature is not mortal.

209
00:17:10,821 --> 00:17:13,282
The story goes back 300 years.

210
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:17,286
Every full moon,
the howling rings through the valley.

211
00:17:17,620 --> 00:17:22,792
Next morning, livestock is found
ripped apart and devoured.

212
00:17:23,042 --> 00:17:27,713
Oh, tales like this just disguise
the work of thieves.

213
00:17:27,797 --> 00:17:29,882
Steal the sheep and blame a wolf,
simple as that.

214
00:17:29,966 --> 00:17:32,510
ROBERT:
But sometimes a child goes missing.

215
00:17:33,302 --> 00:17:37,348
Once in a generation,
a boy will vanish from his homestead.

216
00:17:40,434 --> 00:17:42,144
ISOBEL: Don't, child.

217
00:17:51,571 --> 00:17:54,198
-Who are you?
-Don't enrage him.

218
00:17:54,824 --> 00:17:57,952
Where are you from? You're not from Earth.

219
00:17:59,495 --> 00:18:01,122
What planet are you from?

220
00:18:01,205 --> 00:18:05,293
Oh...intelligence.

221
00:18:05,918 --> 00:18:09,171
-Where were you born?
-This body?

222
00:18:10,631 --> 00:18:12,550
Ten miles away.

223
00:18:13,551 --> 00:18:15,886
A weakling, heartsick boy,

224
00:18:16,178 --> 00:18:20,808
stolen away at night by the Brethren
for my cultivation.

225
00:18:22,268 --> 00:18:26,606
I carved out his soul and sat in his heart.

226
00:18:27,356 --> 00:18:30,610
-Are there descriptions of the creature?
-Oh, yes, Doctor.

227
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:33,321
Drawings and wood carvings.

228
00:18:34,530 --> 00:18:38,367
And it's not merely a wolf,
it's more than that.

229
00:18:39,869 --> 00:18:42,538
This is a man who becomes an animal.

230
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:46,709
A werewolf?

231
00:18:47,376 --> 00:18:50,296
ROSE: All right, so the body's human.

232
00:18:51,797 --> 00:18:54,925
What about you, the thing inside?

233
00:18:55,384 --> 00:18:58,554
So far from home.

234
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:01,474
If you want to get back home, we can help.

235
00:19:02,099 --> 00:19:04,560
Why would I leave this place?

236
00:19:04,769 --> 00:19:08,981
A world of industry,
of workforce and warfare.

237
00:19:09,899 --> 00:19:14,487
-I could turn it to such purpose.
-How would you do that?

238
00:19:14,904 --> 00:19:17,740
I would migrate to the Holy Monarch.

239
00:19:18,199 --> 00:19:19,867
You mean Queen Victoria?

240
00:19:20,076 --> 00:19:23,913
With one bite, I would pass into her blood.

241
00:19:24,914 --> 00:19:28,751
And then it begins, the Empire of the Wolf.

242
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:31,796
So many questions.

243
00:19:36,509 --> 00:19:39,261
Look! Inside your eyes. You've seen it, too.

244
00:19:39,345 --> 00:19:40,429
Seen what?

245
00:19:40,513 --> 00:19:43,516
The wolf.
There is something of the wolf about you.

246
00:19:46,143 --> 00:19:48,229
I don't know what you mean.

247
00:19:48,437 --> 00:19:51,607
Oh, you burn like the sun,

248
00:19:51,732 --> 00:19:55,111
but all I require is the moon.

249
00:19:58,864 --> 00:20:03,119
My father didn't treat it as a story.
He said it was fact.

250
00:20:03,786 --> 00:20:07,581
He even claimed to have communed
with the beast, to have learned its purpose.

251
00:20:08,791 --> 00:20:10,501
I should have listened.

252
00:20:12,211 --> 00:20:14,755
His work was hindered. He made enemies.

253
00:20:14,839 --> 00:20:17,174
There's a monastery
in the Glen of St Catherine.

254
00:20:17,299 --> 00:20:20,678
The Brethren
opposed my father's investigations.

255
00:20:20,761 --> 00:20:23,097
Perhaps they thought his work ungodly.

256
00:20:23,180 --> 00:20:26,100
That's what I thought, but now I wonder.

257
00:20:26,183 --> 00:20:27,935
(FATHER CHANTING IN LATIN)

258
00:20:28,018 --> 00:20:31,981
What if they had a different reason
for wanting the story kept quiet?

259
00:20:32,314 --> 00:20:37,027
What if they turned from God
and worshipped the wolf?

260
00:20:38,487 --> 00:20:40,948
And what if they were with us right now?

261
00:20:49,707 --> 00:20:51,584
Moonlight.

262
00:21:12,521 --> 00:21:14,523
All of you, stop looking at him.

263
00:21:14,607 --> 00:21:18,194
Flora, don't look, listen to me.
Grab hold of the chain and pull!

264
00:21:18,277 --> 00:21:20,988
Come on, with me! Pull!

265
00:21:23,032 --> 00:21:27,244
I said pull! Stop your whining
and listen to me! All of yous!

266
00:21:27,369 --> 00:21:31,373
And that means you, your Ladyship.
Now, come on! Pull!

267
00:21:31,874 --> 00:21:34,210
-What is the meaning of this?
-Explain yourself, sir.

268
00:21:34,293 --> 00:21:35,753
I'm sorry, Your Majesty,
they've got my wife.

269
00:21:35,836 --> 00:21:37,171
Rose, where's Rose? Where is she?

270
00:21:37,254 --> 00:21:38,297
(FATHER CHANTING IN LATIN)

271
00:21:38,380 --> 00:21:39,882
Sir Robert, come on!

272
00:21:50,226 --> 00:21:51,894
...three, pull!

273
00:21:52,394 --> 00:21:57,191
One, two, three, pull!

274
00:21:57,274 --> 00:22:00,194
Tell me, sir.
I demand to know your intention.

275
00:22:00,277 --> 00:22:02,780
(FATHER CHANTING IN LATIN)

276
00:22:02,863 --> 00:22:04,698
What is it that you want?

277
00:22:07,993 --> 00:22:09,453
The throne.

278
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:11,580
(GROANING)

279
00:22:17,461 --> 00:22:19,713
ROSE: ...two, three, pull!

280
00:22:21,715 --> 00:22:25,970
One, two, three,

281
00:22:26,762 --> 00:22:28,430
pull!

282
00:22:34,770 --> 00:22:36,730
Where the hell have you been?

283
00:22:39,733 --> 00:22:42,444
-Oh, that's beautiful.
-Isobel!

284
00:22:44,071 --> 00:22:49,201
Get out, all of you! Come on! Out! Out! Out!

285
00:23:02,631 --> 00:23:06,093
I take it, sir, that you halted my train
to bring me here.

286
00:23:06,176 --> 00:23:08,012
We've waited so long

287
00:23:08,137 --> 00:23:10,222
for one of your journeys
to coincide with the moon.

288
00:23:10,306 --> 00:23:12,141
Then you have waited in vain.

289
00:23:13,100 --> 00:23:16,437
After six attempts on my life,

290
00:23:17,813 --> 00:23:20,024
I am hardly unprepared.

291
00:23:21,817 --> 00:23:24,069
Oh, I don't think so, woman.

292
00:23:24,653 --> 00:23:28,073
The correct form of address
is "Your Majesty".

293
00:23:29,867 --> 00:23:31,285
-Guns.
-I need five.

294
00:23:31,368 --> 00:23:34,246
Lady Isobel, take the girls!
Get them out through the kitchen.

295
00:23:34,330 --> 00:23:35,372
Jackson, at arms...

296
00:23:35,497 --> 00:23:37,041
I can't leave you. What will you do?

297
00:23:37,124 --> 00:23:40,628
I must defend Her Majesty.
Now, don't think of me, just go.

298
00:23:42,171 --> 00:23:44,590
All of you at my side! Come on!

299
00:23:44,965 --> 00:23:46,425
Could be any form of
light-modulating species

300
00:23:46,508 --> 00:23:48,719
triggered by specific wavelengths.
Did it say what it wanted?

301
00:23:48,844 --> 00:23:51,472
The Queen, the crown, the throne,
you name it.

302
00:23:51,555 --> 00:23:53,390
(LOUD CRASHING)

303
00:23:59,521 --> 00:24:01,106
(WEREWOLF GROWLING)

304
00:24:17,706 --> 00:24:21,377
Fire! Fire!

305
00:24:28,050 --> 00:24:31,762
-It won't open. They've sealed us in.
-Oh, my lady, look.

306
00:24:32,638 --> 00:24:34,556
They'll never let us out.

307
00:24:34,682 --> 00:24:37,142
-They mean for us to die.
-Don't say that, Flora!

308
00:24:37,226 --> 00:24:39,603
All right, you men,
we should retreat upstairs. Come with me.

309
00:24:39,728 --> 00:24:41,814
I'll not retreat. The battle's done.

310
00:24:41,897 --> 00:24:45,150
There's no creature on God's earth
could survive such an assault.

311
00:24:45,234 --> 00:24:46,860
I'm telling you, come upstairs!

312
00:24:46,944 --> 00:24:48,570
And I'm telling you, sir,

313
00:24:48,696 --> 00:24:52,074
I will sleep well tonight
with that thing's hide upon my wall.

314
00:24:58,414 --> 00:25:00,082
It must have crawled away to die.

315
00:25:00,165 --> 00:25:01,500
(MAN SCREAMING)

316
00:25:02,543 --> 00:25:04,420
There's nothing we can do!

317
00:25:05,087 --> 00:25:07,089
(GROWLING)

318
00:25:07,423 --> 00:25:08,924
No!

319
00:25:09,717 --> 00:25:10,718
(GUNS FIRING)

320
00:25:10,801 --> 00:25:11,885
(MAN SHOUTING)

321
00:25:12,928 --> 00:25:14,304
Did they kill it?

322
00:25:15,222 --> 00:25:17,933
Come close.

323
00:25:22,438 --> 00:25:24,815
(GROWLING)

324
00:25:34,867 --> 00:25:36,952
(FOOTSTEPS RETREATING)

325
00:25:52,509 --> 00:25:57,056
-Your Majesty, Your Majesty!
-Sir Robert, what's happening?

326
00:25:57,598 --> 00:25:59,224
I heard such terrible noises.

327
00:25:59,308 --> 00:26:01,560
Your Majesty, we've got to get out.

328
00:26:01,685 --> 00:26:04,480
But what of Father Angelo, is he still here?

329
00:26:04,897 --> 00:26:06,273
Captain Reynolds disposed of him.

330
00:26:06,356 --> 00:26:08,317
The front door's no good.
It's been boarded shut.

331
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:11,653
Pardon me, Your Majesty,
you'll have to leg it out of a window.

332
00:26:16,909 --> 00:26:18,702
Excuse my manners, ma'am,

333
00:26:18,786 --> 00:26:21,330
but I shall go first,
the better to assist Her Majesty's egress.

334
00:26:21,455 --> 00:26:22,915
A noble sentiment, my Sir Walter Raleigh.

335
00:26:22,998 --> 00:26:25,292
Yeah, any chance you could hurry up?

336
00:26:31,965 --> 00:26:34,051
I reckon the monky-boys
want us to stay inside.

337
00:26:34,176 --> 00:26:37,346
-Do they know who I am?
-Yeah, that's why they want you.

338
00:26:37,846 --> 00:26:40,474
The wolf's lined you up for a biting.

339
00:26:40,557 --> 00:26:43,977
Now, stop this talk.
There can't be an actual wolf.

340
00:26:44,061 --> 00:26:46,146
(HOWLING)

341
00:26:49,983 --> 00:26:51,401
(BANGING AT DOOR)

342
00:26:51,485 --> 00:26:53,779
-What do we do?
-We run.

343
00:26:53,904 --> 00:26:55,572
-Is that it?
-You got any silver bullets?

344
00:26:55,656 --> 00:26:57,282
-Not on me, no.
-There we are, then. We run.

345
00:26:57,366 --> 00:26:59,368
Your Majesty, as a doctor,
I recommend a vigorous jog,

346
00:26:59,451 --> 00:27:00,911
good for the health.

347
00:27:09,002 --> 00:27:10,587
(WOLF SNARLING)

348
00:27:19,179 --> 00:27:21,390
Come on. Come on.

349
00:27:37,656 --> 00:27:39,867
(YELPING)

350
00:27:39,950 --> 00:27:43,412
I'll take this position and hold it.
You keep moving, for God's sake.

351
00:27:43,495 --> 00:27:46,999
Your Majesty, I went to look
for the property and it was taken.

352
00:27:47,082 --> 00:27:50,252
-The chest was empty.
-I have it. It's safe.

353
00:27:50,752 --> 00:27:52,462
Then remove yourself, ma'am.

354
00:27:52,546 --> 00:27:55,257
Doctor, you stand
as Her Majesty's protector.

355
00:27:55,424 --> 00:28:00,012
And you, Sir Robert.
You're a traitor to the Crown.

356
00:28:00,095 --> 00:28:03,307
-Bullets can't stop it.
-They'll buy you time. Now, run!

357
00:28:21,408 --> 00:28:23,952
(CAPTAIN REYNOLDS SCREAMING)

358
00:28:24,494 --> 00:28:25,829
DOCTOR: Rose!

359
00:28:28,081 --> 00:28:29,791
Barricade the door.

360
00:28:36,965 --> 00:28:39,301
Wait a minute. Shh. Wait, wait, wait. Shh.

361
00:28:39,384 --> 00:28:41,178
(HOWLING)

362
00:28:42,137 --> 00:28:43,639
It stopped.

363
00:29:01,156 --> 00:29:02,324
It's gone.

364
00:29:03,825 --> 00:29:04,910
Listen.

365
00:29:06,995 --> 00:29:09,414
(WOLF SNARLING)

366
00:29:09,498 --> 00:29:12,834
(PAWS STOMPING)

367
00:29:13,961 --> 00:29:17,631
-(WHISPERING) Is this the only door?
-Yes.

368
00:29:18,173 --> 00:29:19,466
No!

369
00:29:19,675 --> 00:29:21,551
(SNARLING)

370
00:29:26,431 --> 00:29:27,891
ROSE: Shh!

371
00:29:31,728 --> 00:29:33,188
(WOOD CREAKING)

372
00:29:35,274 --> 00:29:37,067
(PANTING)

373
00:29:41,947 --> 00:29:44,283
(SNARLING)

374
00:29:45,826 --> 00:29:46,952
(STEPS RETREATING)

375
00:29:47,035 --> 00:29:50,080
I don't understand. What's stopping it?

376
00:29:53,917 --> 00:29:55,877
Something inside this room.

377
00:29:57,504 --> 00:29:59,589
What is it? Why can't it get in?

378
00:30:00,757 --> 00:30:03,677
-I tell you what, though.
-What?

379
00:30:03,760 --> 00:30:05,887
-Werewolf.
-I know!

380
00:30:08,598 --> 00:30:10,767
-You all right?
-I'm okay, yeah.

381
00:30:11,393 --> 00:30:12,811
I'm sorry, ma'am.

382
00:30:15,230 --> 00:30:16,982
It's all my fault.

383
00:30:18,066 --> 00:30:19,776
I should have sent you away.

384
00:30:21,028 --> 00:30:25,198
I tried to suggest something was wrong.
I thought you might notice.

385
00:30:26,033 --> 00:30:28,952
Did you think there was nothing strange
about my household staff?

386
00:30:29,036 --> 00:30:30,746
Well, they were bald, athletic.

387
00:30:30,829 --> 00:30:33,540
Your wife's away,
I just thought you were happy.

388
00:30:35,208 --> 00:30:37,961
I'll tell you what though, ma'am,
I bet you're not amused now.

389
00:30:38,045 --> 00:30:41,298
-Do you think this funny?
-No, ma'am, I'm sorry.

390
00:30:41,381 --> 00:30:44,343
What, exactly, I pray,
tell me, someone, please,

391
00:30:44,426 --> 00:30:47,387
what exactly is that creature?

392
00:30:48,180 --> 00:30:49,222
You'd call it a werewolf,

393
00:30:49,306 --> 00:30:51,975
but technically it's more
of a lupine-wavelength haemovariform.

394
00:30:52,059 --> 00:30:56,605
And should I trust you, sir?
You, who change your voice so easily?

395
00:30:56,855 --> 00:30:58,774
What happened to your accent?

396
00:30:59,441 --> 00:31:02,319
-Oh, right, sorry, that...
-I'll not have it.

397
00:31:02,778 --> 00:31:07,157
No, sir. Not you, not that thing, none of it.

398
00:31:08,075 --> 00:31:10,952
This is not my world.

399
00:31:15,582 --> 00:31:17,209
Mistletoe.

400
00:31:17,292 --> 00:31:20,420
They're all garlanded in mistletoe
and the wolf doesn't attack them.

401
00:31:21,421 --> 00:31:25,217
-Who brought this into the kitchen?
-Must have been the Brethren.

402
00:31:25,884 --> 00:31:30,013
Gather it up, quickly.
Every last scrap. Quick, now!

403
00:31:35,811 --> 00:31:37,145
Mistletoe.

404
00:31:38,647 --> 00:31:41,316
Sir Robert, did your father put that there?

405
00:31:41,817 --> 00:31:43,860
I don't know. I suppose.

406
00:31:44,069 --> 00:31:45,862
And on the other door, too.

407
00:31:46,154 --> 00:31:48,323
Though a carving wouldn't be enough.

408
00:31:49,116 --> 00:31:50,325
I wonder.

409
00:31:53,328 --> 00:31:54,704
Viscum album, the oil of the mistletoe.

410
00:31:54,788 --> 00:31:56,498
It's been worked into the wood
like a varnish.

411
00:31:56,581 --> 00:31:58,959
How clever was your dad? I love him!

412
00:31:59,042 --> 00:32:01,962
Powerful stuff, mistletoe,
bursting with lectins and viscotoxins.

413
00:32:02,045 --> 00:32:04,131
-And the wolf's allergic to it?
-Or it thinks it is.

414
00:32:04,214 --> 00:32:06,091
The monky-monk-monks need a way
of controlling the wolf,

415
00:32:06,174 --> 00:32:07,926
maybe they trained it
to react against certain things.

416
00:32:08,009 --> 00:32:10,595
Nevertheless,
that creature won't give up, Doctor,

417
00:32:10,679 --> 00:32:13,140
and we still don't possess
an actual weapon.

418
00:32:13,223 --> 00:32:15,267
Oh, your father got all the brains,
didn't he?

419
00:32:15,350 --> 00:32:18,103
-Being rude again.
-Good, I meant that one.

420
00:32:18,186 --> 00:32:20,856
You want weapons?
We're in a library. Books!

421
00:32:21,398 --> 00:32:23,692
Best weapons in the world.

422
00:32:24,860 --> 00:32:27,112
This room is the greatest arsenal
we could have.

423
00:32:28,989 --> 00:32:30,574
Arm yourself.

424
00:32:33,702 --> 00:32:37,247
There's no sound of the wolf, my lady,
perhaps it's gone.

425
00:32:37,456 --> 00:32:39,416
And perhaps it's toying with us.

426
00:32:39,499 --> 00:32:40,959
But my husband's up there,

427
00:32:41,042 --> 00:32:44,629
and if there's any chance he's still alive,
then, by God, I'll assist him.

428
00:32:49,634 --> 00:32:51,845
Look up biology and zoology.

429
00:32:51,928 --> 00:32:53,722
-There might be something on wolves.
-DOCTOR: What about this?

430
00:32:53,889 --> 00:32:56,183
-A whole book on mistletoe.
-ROBERT: "The application of gunpowder..."

431
00:32:56,266 --> 00:32:59,311
-If we could build some form of explosive.
-Hmm, that's the sort of thing.

432
00:32:59,394 --> 00:33:00,770
Ohhh.

433
00:33:02,314 --> 00:33:05,734
Look what your old dad found.
Something fell to Earth.

434
00:33:05,817 --> 00:33:08,320
-A spaceship?
-Shooting star.

435
00:33:08,737 --> 00:33:13,033
"In the year of our Lord 1540,
under the reign of King James V,

436
00:33:13,116 --> 00:33:15,869
"an almighty fire did burn in the pit.”

437
00:33:16,328 --> 00:33:18,872
That's the Glen of Saint Catherine,
just by the monastery.

438
00:33:18,955 --> 00:33:21,917
But that's over 300 years ago.
What's it been waiting for?

439
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:25,921
Maybe just a single cell survived.
Adapting slowly down the generations,

440
00:33:26,004 --> 00:33:29,799
it survived through the humans,
host after host after host.

441
00:33:29,925 --> 00:33:31,343
But why does it want the throne?

442
00:33:31,426 --> 00:33:35,889
That's what it wants, it said so.
The Empire of the Wolf.

443
00:33:36,264 --> 00:33:39,768
Imagine it. The Victorian Age accelerated.

444
00:33:40,644 --> 00:33:44,481
Starships and missiles fuel led by coal
and driven by steam,

445
00:33:45,941 --> 00:33:48,610
leaving history devastated in its wake.

446
00:33:49,361 --> 00:33:54,533
-Sir Robert. If I am to die here...
-Don't say that, Your Majesty.

447
00:33:55,116 --> 00:33:59,788
...] would destroy myself
rather than let that creature infect me,

448
00:33:59,955 --> 00:34:01,122
but that's no matter.

449
00:34:01,206 --> 00:34:03,792
I ask only that you find
some place of safekeeping

450
00:34:03,959 --> 00:34:07,504
for something far older
and more precious than myself.

451
00:34:07,587 --> 00:34:09,881
Hardly the time
to worry about your valuables.

452
00:34:09,965 --> 00:34:11,967
Thank you for your opinion,

453
00:34:12,842 --> 00:34:15,929
but there is nothing
more valuable than this.

454
00:34:16,972 --> 00:34:18,723
ROBERT: Oh, Your Majesty.

455
00:34:21,226 --> 00:34:24,479
-Is that the Koh-i-noor?
-Oh, yes.

456
00:34:25,397 --> 00:34:27,732
The greatest diamond in the world.

457
00:34:27,816 --> 00:34:29,985
Given to me as the spoils of war.

458
00:34:31,152 --> 00:34:33,446
Perhaps its legend is now coming true.

459
00:34:33,530 --> 00:34:36,783
It is said that whoever owns it
must surely die.

460
00:34:36,866 --> 00:34:40,412
Well, that's true of anything,
if you wait long enough. Can I?

461
00:34:49,004 --> 00:34:52,048
-That is so beautiful.
-How much is that worth?

462
00:34:52,173 --> 00:34:56,970
They say, the wages of the entire planet
for a whole week.

463
00:34:57,512 --> 00:34:58,638
Good job my mum's not here,

464
00:34:58,722 --> 00:35:01,266
she'd be fighting the wolf off
with her bare hands for that thing.

465
00:35:01,349 --> 00:35:04,102
-And she'd win.
-Where is the wolf?

466
00:35:05,520 --> 00:35:08,815
-I don't trust this silence.
-Why do you travel with it?

467
00:35:09,190 --> 00:35:10,817
My annual pilgrimage.

468
00:35:10,900 --> 00:35:16,114
I'm taking it to Hellier and Carew,
the Royal Jewellers at Hazlehead.

469
00:35:16,323 --> 00:35:18,450
The stone needs recutting.

470
00:35:18,992 --> 00:35:22,329
-But it's perfect.
-My late husband never thought so.

471
00:35:22,412 --> 00:35:23,913
Now, there's a fact.

472
00:35:24,080 --> 00:35:26,291
Prince Albert kept on having
the Koh-i-noor cut down.

473
00:35:26,374 --> 00:35:30,128
It used to be 40% bigger than this,
but he was never happy.

474
00:35:30,211 --> 00:35:32,088
Kept on cutting and cutting.

475
00:35:32,213 --> 00:35:36,676
He always said
the shine was not quite right,

476
00:35:37,344 --> 00:35:40,388
but he died with it still unfinished.

477
00:35:42,974 --> 00:35:44,643
Unfinished.

478
00:35:47,145 --> 00:35:48,396
Oh, yes!

479
00:35:48,480 --> 00:35:50,231
There's a lot of unfinished business
in this house.

480
00:35:50,315 --> 00:35:51,816
His father's research
and your husband, ma'am.

481
00:35:51,900 --> 00:35:53,735
He came here
and he sought the perfect diamond.

482
00:35:53,860 --> 00:35:54,986
Hold on, oh, hold on.

483
00:35:55,070 --> 00:35:56,321
All these separate things,

484
00:35:56,404 --> 00:35:57,739
they're not separate at all,
they're connected.

485
00:35:57,822 --> 00:35:59,032
Oh, my head, my head!

486
00:35:59,115 --> 00:36:01,826
What if this house... It's a trap for you.
Is that right, ma"am?

487
00:36:01,910 --> 00:36:03,953
-Obviously.
-At least, that's what the wolf intended,

488
00:36:04,079 --> 00:36:06,289
but what if there's a trap inside the trap?

489
00:36:06,414 --> 00:36:07,749
Explain yourself, Doctor.

490
00:36:07,874 --> 00:36:10,919
What if his father and your husband
weren't just telling each other stories.

491
00:36:11,044 --> 00:36:14,005
They dared to imagine all this was true,
and they planned against it.

492
00:36:14,089 --> 00:36:17,967
Laying the real trap not for you,
but for the wolf.

493
00:36:25,266 --> 00:36:27,185
That wolf, there.

494
00:36:29,813 --> 00:36:31,940
DOCTOR: Out! Out! Out! Out!

495
00:36:32,899 --> 00:36:34,442
DOCTOR: Your Majesty!

496
00:36:40,281 --> 00:36:42,492
We've got to get to the observatory!

497
00:36:47,372 --> 00:36:48,832
(ROSE SCREAMING)

498
00:36:49,124 --> 00:36:50,333
(WOLF BURNING)

499
00:36:50,458 --> 00:36:53,211
DOCTOR: Good shot!
FLORA: It was mistletoe.

500
00:36:53,294 --> 00:36:54,629
Isobel.

501
00:36:56,005 --> 00:36:59,384
-ROBERT: Now get back downstairs.
-Keep yourself safe.

502
00:36:59,759 --> 00:37:02,679
My love. Now, go.

503
00:37:02,929 --> 00:37:04,931
Girls, come with me.

504
00:37:05,014 --> 00:37:07,308
Down the back stairs
back to the kitchens, quickly.

505
00:37:07,475 --> 00:37:08,476
Come on.

506
00:37:08,935 --> 00:37:10,770
The observatory is this way.

507
00:37:22,949 --> 00:37:24,325
No mistletoe on these doors,

508
00:37:24,451 --> 00:37:25,910
'cause your father wanted
the wolf to get inside.

509
00:37:25,994 --> 00:37:27,954
I just need time.
Is there any way of barricading this?

510
00:37:28,037 --> 00:37:29,247
Do your work, and I'll defend it.

511
00:37:29,330 --> 00:37:31,249
If we could bind them shut
with rope or something...

512
00:37:31,332 --> 00:37:34,836
I said I'll find you time, sir.
Now, get inside.

513
00:37:36,671 --> 00:37:37,839
Good man.

514
00:37:38,673 --> 00:37:40,175
Your Majesty, the diamond.

515
00:37:40,258 --> 00:37:43,344
-For what purpose?
-The purpose it was designed for.

516
00:37:47,056 --> 00:37:48,516
(WOLF GROWLING)

517
00:37:54,022 --> 00:37:55,106
Rose.

518
00:37:57,567 --> 00:37:58,943
Lift it, come on.

519
00:38:01,237 --> 00:38:03,907
-Not the right time for stargazing.
-Yes, it is.

520
00:38:03,990 --> 00:38:05,033
(DOCTOR GROANING)

521
00:38:12,040 --> 00:38:13,833
(WOLF GROWLING)

522
00:38:15,877 --> 00:38:18,338
I committed treason for you,

523
00:38:19,798 --> 00:38:23,760
but now my wife
will remember me with honour.

524
00:38:27,680 --> 00:38:29,516
(ROBERT SCREAMING)

525
00:38:32,560 --> 00:38:34,813
(BANGING AT DOOR)

526
00:38:34,896 --> 00:38:37,649
I am the Defender of the Faith,
and that Faith shall defend me.

527
00:38:37,732 --> 00:38:39,150
You said this thing doesn't work.

528
00:38:39,275 --> 00:38:41,569
It doesn't work as a telescope,
"cause that's not what it is.

529
00:38:41,694 --> 00:38:44,405
It's a light chamber.
It magnifies the light, like a weapon.

530
00:38:44,531 --> 00:38:48,326
-We've just got to power it up.
-With what? There's no electricity.

531
00:38:50,286 --> 00:38:53,540
Moonlight. But the wolf needs moonlight.
It's made by moonlight.

532
00:38:53,623 --> 00:38:56,960
You're 70% water, you can still drown.
Come on!

533
00:39:01,422 --> 00:39:02,632
Come on!

534
00:39:43,798 --> 00:39:46,509
Make it brighter. Let me go.

535
00:40:08,489 --> 00:40:10,992
(HOWLING)

536
00:40:25,131 --> 00:40:26,341
Your Majesty?

537
00:40:28,885 --> 00:40:30,303
Did it bite you?

538
00:40:30,511 --> 00:40:34,349
No, it's... It's a cut, that's all.

539
00:40:36,184 --> 00:40:37,936
If that thing bit you...

540
00:40:39,020 --> 00:40:42,899
It was a splinter of wood
when the door came apart. It's nothing.

541
00:40:44,692 --> 00:40:46,861
-Let me see.
-It is nothing.

542
00:40:55,662 --> 00:40:58,122
By the power invested in me
by the Church and the State,

543
00:40:58,206 --> 00:41:03,044
I dub thee Sir Doctor of Tardis.

544
00:41:04,212 --> 00:41:06,881
By the power invested in me
by the Church and the State,

545
00:41:07,006 --> 00:41:12,387
I dub thee Dame Rose of the Powell Estate.

546
00:41:12,637 --> 00:41:13,888
You may stand.

547
00:41:15,390 --> 00:41:16,557
Many thanks, ma'am.

548
00:41:16,641 --> 00:41:19,435
Thanks. They're never gonna believe this
back home.

549
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:21,312
Your Majesty, you said last night

550
00:41:21,396 --> 00:41:24,190
about receiving no message
from the great beyond.

551
00:41:24,774 --> 00:41:27,777
I think your husband cut that diamond
to save your life.

552
00:41:27,902 --> 00:41:31,656
He's protecting you even now, ma'am,
from beyond the grave.

553
00:41:31,739 --> 00:41:33,741
Indeed.

554
00:41:33,825 --> 00:41:38,663
Then you may think on this also,
that I am not amused.

555
00:41:39,372 --> 00:41:40,748
Yes!

556
00:41:40,957 --> 00:41:44,419
Not remotely amused.

557
00:41:44,794 --> 00:41:48,339
And henceforth, I banish you.

558
00:41:49,215 --> 00:41:50,258
I'm sorry?

559
00:41:50,383 --> 00:41:52,260
I have rewarded you, Sir Doctor,

560
00:41:52,343 --> 00:41:56,431
and now you are exiled from this Empire,
never to return.

561
00:41:58,558 --> 00:42:02,603
I don't know what you are, the two of you,
or where you're from,

562
00:42:03,438 --> 00:42:08,067
but I know that you consort
with stars and magic, and think it fun.

563
00:42:08,651 --> 00:42:13,156
But your world is steeped in terror
and blasphemy and death,

564
00:42:13,281 --> 00:42:15,825
and I will not allow it.

565
00:42:16,284 --> 00:42:20,288
You will leave these shores,
and you will reflect, I hope,

566
00:42:20,413 --> 00:42:25,168
on how you came to stray so far
from all that is good,

567
00:42:25,501 --> 00:42:29,881
and how much longer
you may survive this terrible life.

568
00:42:33,468 --> 00:42:35,803
Now leave my world,

569
00:42:36,804 --> 00:42:39,515
and never return.

570
00:42:41,017 --> 00:42:43,603
-Whoa!
-Cheers!

571
00:42:45,521 --> 00:42:46,981
-Walk on.
-No, but the funny thing is,

572
00:42:47,065 --> 00:42:49,233
Queen Victoria actually did suffer
a mutation of the blood.

573
00:42:49,358 --> 00:42:51,319
It's historical record.
She was haemophiliac.

574
00:42:51,402 --> 00:42:52,737
They used to call it the Royal Disease,

575
00:42:52,820 --> 00:42:55,073
but it's always been a mystery
because she didn't inherit it.

576
00:42:55,156 --> 00:42:56,783
Her mum didn't have it.
Her dad didn't have it.

577
00:42:56,866 --> 00:42:59,494
-It came from nowhere.
-What, and you're saying that's a wolf bite?

578
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:02,747
Well, maybe haemophilia is
just a Victorian euphemism.

579
00:43:02,830 --> 00:43:04,499
-For werewolf?
-Could be.

580
00:43:05,166 --> 00:43:07,168
-Queen Victoria's a werewolf?
-Could be.

581
00:43:07,251 --> 00:43:11,547
And her children had the Royal Disease.
Maybe she gave them a quick nip.

582
00:43:12,131 --> 00:43:14,884
-So the Royal Family are werewolves?
-Well, maybe not yet.

583
00:43:14,967 --> 00:43:19,347
I mean, a single wolf cell could take
100 years to mature.

584
00:43:19,472 --> 00:43:23,559
Might be ready by, oh, early 21st century.

585
00:43:23,643 --> 00:43:25,812
No, that's just ridiculous.

586
00:43:26,437 --> 00:43:29,398
-Mind you, Princess Anne.
-I'll say no more.

587
00:43:29,774 --> 00:43:33,528
And if you think about it,
they're very private.

588
00:43:33,611 --> 00:43:35,530
They plan everything in advance.

589
00:43:35,655 --> 00:43:39,158
They could schedule themselves
around the moon. We'd never know.

590
00:43:39,242 --> 00:43:43,204
And they like hunting.
They love blood sports.

591
00:43:43,287 --> 00:43:44,288
(DOCTOR LAUGHING)

592
00:43:44,372 --> 00:43:47,333
Oh, my God! They're werewolves!

593
00:43:47,458 --> 00:43:49,377
(BOTH LAUGHING)

594
00:43:49,710 --> 00:43:51,629
(BOTH HOWLING)

595
00:43:51,712 --> 00:43:53,297
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

596
00:43:56,467 --> 00:43:58,386
What will you do? Will you stay here?

597
00:43:59,720 --> 00:44:01,556
I don't think I could.

598
00:44:02,932 --> 00:44:06,853
I'd sell it, or pull this place down.

599
00:44:11,399 --> 00:44:15,987
Although we may not speak of these events
in public, they will not be forgotten.

600
00:44:16,237 --> 00:44:17,738
I promise you that.

601
00:44:18,573 --> 00:44:23,161
Your husband's sacrifice,
the ingenuity of his father,

602
00:44:23,828 --> 00:44:25,079
they will live on.

603
00:44:25,204 --> 00:44:26,581
But how?

604
00:44:27,248 --> 00:44:28,791
I saw, last night,

605
00:44:28,875 --> 00:44:32,879
that Great Britain has enemies
beyond imagination,

606
00:44:32,962 --> 00:44:36,257
and we must defend our borders
on all sides.

607
00:44:37,842 --> 00:44:40,928
I propose an institute

608
00:44:41,262 --> 00:44:44,849
to investigate these strange happenings
and to fight them.

609
00:44:46,350 --> 00:44:51,439
I would call it Torchwood.
The Torchwood Institute.

610
00:44:51,522 --> 00:44:55,943
And if this Doctor should return,
then he should beware,

611
00:44:56,485 --> 00:44:59,113
because Torchwood will be waiting.

612
00:45:04,160 --> 00:45:06,204
Good morning, class.

613
00:45:06,579 --> 00:45:07,622
Are we sitting comfortably?

614
00:45:08,915 --> 00:45:11,375
Three months ago, turns out
all the kitchen staff were replaced.

615
00:45:11,459 --> 00:45:14,128
See? There's definitely something going on.
I was right to call you home.

616
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:16,547
May I introduce Miss Sarah Jane Smith.

617
00:45:16,631 --> 00:45:18,007
-Nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you!

618
00:45:18,090 --> 00:45:19,383
Yes. Very nice.

619
00:45:19,467 --> 00:45:22,637
You are not permitted to leave your station
during a sitting.

620
00:45:22,720 --> 00:45:25,723
Boy in class this morning,
got knowledge way beyond planet Earth.

621
00:45:27,725 --> 00:45:29,352
KO!

622
00:45:29,477 --> 00:45:34,232
Our time has come, my brothers.
Today we shall become gods.

